==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tupelo
<hw>Tu"pe*lo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Tupelo</ets>,
or <ets>tupebo</ets>, the native American Indian name.]</ety>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A North American tree (<spn>Nyssa
multiflora</spn>) of the Dogwood family, having brilliant, glossy
foliage and acid red berries. The wood is crossgrained and very
difficult to split. Called also <altname>black gum</altname>,
<altname>sour gum</altname>, and
<altname>pepperidge</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Largo tupelo</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Tupelo
gum</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an American tree (<spn>Nyssa
uniflora</spn>) with softer wood than the tupelo.</cd> -- <col><b>Sour
tupelo</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the Ogeechee lime.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tupi</ent>⟦br⟧
